    <section id="networking-ip-suite">
        <title>IP Suite</title>

        <subsection id="networking-ip-suite-layer-descriptions" answers_as_choices="true" and_reverse="true">
            <title>Layers Descriptions</title>
            <link>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_protocol_suite#Abstraction_layers</link>

            <question id="networking-ip-suite-layer-descriptions-link">
                <text>Link Layer</text>
                <answer>Physical and logical interconnection of hosts (nodes) in the same network.</answer>
                <link>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Link_layer</link>
                <note>Roughly, this is a combination of the OSI Model's Data Link layer and Physical layer. At this layer, Ethernet, transports "Ethernet frames"</note>
            </question>

            <question id="networking-ip-suite-layer-descriptions-internet">
                <text>Internet Layer</text>
                <answer>Internetworking: Transports datagrams between hosts, even between networks. Hosts have IP addresses.</answer>
                <link>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_layer</link>
                <note>At this layer, IP transports "IP datagrams".</note>
            </question>

            <question id="networking-ip-suite-layer-descriptions-transport">
                <text>Transport Layer</text>
                <answer>Communication between hosts, optionally with connections, data streams, reliability, flow control and multiplexing.</answer>
                <link>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transport_layer</link>
                <note>At this layer, TCP transports "TCP segments", or UDP transports "UDP datagrams".</note>
            </question>

            <question id="networking-ip-suite-layer-descriptions-application">
                <text>Application Layer</text>
                <answer>Process-to-process communication between hosts.</answer>
                <link>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Application_layer</link>
            </question>
        </subsection>

